<div class="content-panel standalone series">
<p><a name="operational"></a></p>
<table style="border: none; width: 100%;">
<tr>
<td><span style="font-size:125%;"><strong>Item #:</strong> SCP-CRNP</span></td>
<td style="text-align: right;"></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td><span style="font-size:125%;"><strong>Object Class:</strong> <span style="text-decoration: line-through;">Reasonably Safe</span> <tt>NEUTRALIZED</tt></span></td>
<td style="text-align: right;"></td>
</tr>
</table>
<hr />
<h2 id="toc0"><span>How would you describe the SCP Foundation to someone? What does this community mean to you?</span></h2>
<p>The SCP Foundation is a community of authors, readers, and voters (but primarily the last two) who by creating something of no apparent material value or capital gain, are a shining example of the internet of old, where people came together to collaborate for the sheer value of interpersonal creation and respect for a craft. Their formal creative writing template is a stroke of genius, and should be remembered by history as a generational export. The format helps fill a species-wide void by nurturing an essential exceptionalism to the consilient, agnostic preponderance for certainty in our increasingly scientific paradigm.</p>
<p>The community can be cast as three classes: a ruling class (staff), a production class (writers), and a consumption class (readers). There is obviously overlap between all of these.</p>
<script type="text/javascript" src="http://d3g0gp89917ko0.cloudfront.net/v--3e3a6f7dbcc9/common--javascript/yahooui/tabview-min.js">
</script>
<div id="wiki-tabview-a6ca04a08c01a315102ceea072cc6dad" class="yui-navset">
<ul class="yui-nav">
<li class="selected"><a href="javascript:;"><em>The Ruling Class</em></a></li>
<li><a href="javascript:;"><em>Production-Class</em></a></li>
<li><a href="javascript:;"><em>Consumption-Class</em></a></li>
</ul>
<div class="yui-content">
<div id="wiki-tab-0-0">
<p>The ruling class is comprised of members who have positioned themselves, whether via successful articles or longevity in the community (or both), into a version of the hierarchy structure that they fictionalize, complete with specialization and action teams. This is grueling, unpayed work. But people still choose to do it (because that’s not to say they don’t get “paid” in some way), and are looked up to by the community as leaders.</p>
<p>Perhaps unexpectedly or unsurprisingly, those of the ruling-class are not immune to various forms of morally questionable misuse of their position and authority, including: verbal abuse, multiple &quot;puppet&quot; account infractions, source-code manipulation for private gain, mission/power creep, forms of connivance including but not limited to the covert sabotaging of others' works (particularly in contests) &amp; overt promotion of their own/select others' works (particularly in contests), suppression of community voice, unequal application of site norms, judgments, and punishments (with particular leniency given towards others in the ruling class), the deployment of mob-level responses to disagreed-with opinions or positions for the purpose of (permanent) censorship, and procedural incompetence.<sup class="footnoteref"><a id="footnoteref-1" href="javascript:;" class="footnoteref" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.utils.scrollToReference('footnote-1')">1</a></sup></p>
<p>These individuals are functionally a dominant class and have a tendency to lord their experience, leverage, and brand/icon recognition (not to mention all the clout of a meaningless &quot;Karma&quot; system per Wikidot) to exert influence on other members of the community; on anything from policy, to the valuation of a given article, to the set of ideas that are deemed acceptable to write about.</p>
<p>The structure deployed by the ruling-class means certain qualities are inevitable, deducible from the premises. The meritocratic nature of the way in which new members of the ruling class are selected/approved of<sup class="footnoteref"><a id="footnoteref-2" href="javascript:;" class="footnoteref" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.utils.scrollToReference('footnote-2')">2</a></sup> cultures sycophants within the production and consumption classes but also potential ire; both entail undue and asymmetrical application of article judgement and valuation (particularly to the detriment of either established-quality authors, or the fuel-source and core-level kinesiology of the site, new authors). Thus, unfortunately here, as is the case in less noble ventures, might makes right and those who desire authority are usually the least qualified morally to have it.<sup class="footnoteref"><a id="footnoteref-3" href="javascript:;" class="footnoteref" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.utils.scrollToReference('footnote-3')">3</a></sup></p>
</div>
<div id="wiki-tab-0-1" style="display:none">
<p>A production-class of authors (who are not staff) work to contribute under the highly xenophobic and initially-abusive posture of this ruling class. Some of these have ambitions to join the ruling class, while others are content to write and be part of the community (and even fewer are disgusted by the structure, and tolerate it, barely hanging on to the community, remembering what's expressed in the first paragraph of this response as a sort of hope). Members of this class are typically motivated by quantitative metrics of success for their works, namely the article's displayed rating module number (see <em>Consumption-Class</em>), which is awarded as totally authoritative with respect to a work's value and worth for inclusion, per the ruling class.</p>
<p>Authors are required to undergo a <span style="text-decoration: line-through;">hazing</span> conditioning program where an idea must be subjected to abusive and eager critics (most importantly when by members of the ruling-class). The suggestions of the criticisms are expected to be incorporated into the work and an article may be invalidated based on a failure to apply recommended changes, in essence conforming an article to the expectations of the consumption-class.</p>
<p>Ideally, those of this class who have no overlap with the ruling-class would be the only ones allowed to vote, keeping the community's standards and products of the highest quality while avoiding article subjugation to the lagging palate of the consuming masses.</p>
</div>
<div id="wiki-tab-0-2" style="display:none">
<p>An overwhelming majority of the (near adolescent) voting members typically wouldn't know good writing if H.P. Lovecraft signed it for them. To these members, the site is strictly a consumable popularity contest, unfortunately predicated on surface features more than anything else. Articles are paraded across the proverbial stage like contestants of a beauty pageant, and are scrutinized meticulously (primarily by the ruling-class, but recall that their behavior is memetically copied to the other classes). Articles that are not immediately satiating to a majority of readers, who typically are at-the-ready for immediate consumption and processing, are dismissed as unworthy.</p>
<p>So submitted articles are received <em>a priori</em> and asymmetrically according to author's brand (who may or may not reveal that they're the one behind the article <em>as soon as is possible in the read</em>&#8230; but most readers will check to see who wrote it before reading it&#8230; if that doesn't say something to you about the nature of the community&#8230;), in some cases exclusively. This produces a muscle memory that prioritizes conformity over depth, commodity over culture, and nepotism over a (lost) fidelity to rigorous standards of composition and creative thought; in short, it favors spectacle over substance. This is acceptable to the ruling class, as they are currently ruling.<sup class="footnoteref"><a id="footnoteref-4" href="javascript:;" class="footnoteref" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.utils.scrollToReference('footnote-4')">4</a></sup></p>
<p>An assurance that the ruling-class will structurally perpetuate its totality of environmental control &#8212; and provide an “objective” prop by which to deflect their culpability in the disfigured architecture of the site &#8212; is concretely expressed in the mandatory inclusion of a simulated act of shared power, the effect of which for the other classes is the feeling of inclusion; by it, even the least member of the site believes that their opinion matters and that they have a tangible, democratic say. In practice, the act is more authoritarian than its democratic veneer would have one believe. Upvotes and downvotes are dangled out like bait &#8212; as if they were the most appealing and edifying part of the creative process &#8212; to authors in the comments of their works and behind closed doors. The presumed power to give a drool-worthy “+1” or a terrifying “-1” is used by anyone as a means of manipulative bartering in order to direct the terms of acceptance and mimic importance.</p>
<p>Upvotes are incessantly campaigned for in a stench of unexcused self-promotion &#8212; not because of a lack of confidence that an article is good, but worse, for the sake of decorative opulence and bragging rights that are a cancer of excess.<sup class="footnoteref"><a id="footnoteref-5" href="javascript:;" class="footnoteref" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.utils.scrollToReference('footnote-5')">5</a></sup> They are &quot;exchanged&quot; in the name of mutualism, consented to in private messages, with disregard for the basis of the act's value, which is only as meaningful as these compromises with dignity, and so devalued instantly. The upvote/downvote has been stratospherically inflated into near-absolute representational meaninglessness.</p>
<p>The currents underlying this form of currency are not in a small way directed covertly by the ruling class, initially between themselves and then to their dependent classes (who sometimes wait on them for a judgment to adopt and follow). A call to action by a sufficiently influential member or members can enshrine an entry, change the minds of previously-decided members, or destroy an opinion deemed in need of censorship &#8212; all at will and with a haste that is incompatible with careful thought or just processing.<sup class="footnoteref"><a id="footnoteref-6" href="javascript:;" class="footnoteref" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.utils.scrollToReference('footnote-6')">6</a></sup></p>
<p>This function is primarily used by the consumption-class, who by definition lack the requisite creativity and/or motivation to maneuver within (and not just on the periphery of) the power paradigm, and so act essentially as clones for the exaggerated, dictated idiosyncrasies of the ruling class. Structurally, this reinforces the status quo established by the ruling-class to the effect of sandwiching the production class in a disingenuous &amp; manufactured solidarity. The culmination of this pantomime of democracy, this false act of participatory power, this “free-market” method of evaluation, and this institutional shell-game is called the <span style="text-decoration: line-through;">baiting</span> rating module.</p>
<p>The rating module, which itself is slothfully conceptualized then propagandized as the only viable solution (and so weakly justified after, if only in its positioning relative to the article's content), is prominently displayed in the upper right corner of each publication.<sup class="footnoteref"><a id="footnoteref-7" href="javascript:;" class="footnoteref" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.utils.scrollToReference('footnote-7')">7</a></sup> The officially-cited role of the rating module (and the within-24-hour deletion process that serves as its only non-collapsible justification) favors the need for articles to be immediately appealing, necessarily excluding qualities of writing that can be characteristic of great works of literature, such as the ability to be sufficiently ahead of their time, or to challenge a stagnant palate. Unlike in other mediums, such initially-rejected works are lost or at best, associated as salvage operations, which represents a ceiling for the art form, and is a shame because it doesn’t have to be there in the first place.</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<script type="text/javascript">
